│                                                                              │
│ ## Documented tradeoffs                                                      │
│                                                                              │
│ ### 1. Runtime-entrypoint view vs. package-dependency view                   │
│                                                                              │
│ **Package-dependency view** is strong for repo topology because package      │
│ manifests and workspace files reveal boundaries and dependency direction     │
│ [4].                                                                         │
│ **Runtime-entrypoint view** is stronger for active behavior because it shows │
│ what actually runs, e.g. `runtime/shell/src/commands/fs.ts` and semantic     │
│ search tests [2][3][4].                                                      │
│                                                                              │
│ Decision: **Use runtime/source/test evidence for active claims; use          │
│ manifests for subsystem boundaries** [1][4].                                 │
│                                                                              │
│ ---                                                                          │
│                                                                              │
│ ### 2. Monorepo structure vs. product subsystem structure                    │
│                                                                              │
│ The repository layout (`core/`, `runtime/`, `packages/`, `apps/`,            │
│ `cartridges/`, `tools/`, `configs/`, `db/`, `scripts/`) is concrete and      │
│ auditable [2][4].                                                            │
│ But product subsystems span directories: for example, “SemanticFS/search”    │
│ crosses `runtime/shell` and `core/protocol-types`; “extraction” crosses      │
│ `packages/extraction`, `runtime-services`, `protocol-types`, and SIR [2][3]. │
│                                                                              │
│ Decision: **Present a product subsystem map, but cite concrete source paths  │
│ for each subsystem** [4].                                                    │
│                                                                              │
│ ---                                                                          │
│                                                                              │
│ ### 3. Manifest evidence vs. implementation usage                            │
│                                                                              │
│ Manifests prove package identity, exports, scripts, dependencies, and app    │
│ composition. They do not prove production/runtime execution [1][3][4].       │
│                                                                              │
│ Examples:                                                                    │
│                                                                              │
│ - `core/semantos-sir/package.json` proves SIR package boundary and           │
│ dependency on IR, lexicon, SCG [2].                                          │
│ - It does **not** prove every SIR lowering path is invoked by the app or     │
│ runtime [6].                                                                 │
│ - `apps/semantos/pubspec.yaml` proves the Flutter shell app declares         │
│ cartridge, identity, LLM/STT, and FFI dependencies [2].                      │
│ - It does **not** prove every declared dependency is exercised at runtime    │
│ [3][6].                                                                      │
│                                                                              │
│ Decision: **Manifest-only components are “partial / manifest-confirmed”      │
│ unless accompanied by source/test/runtime caller evidence** [1][3].          │
│                                                                              │
│ ---                                                                          │
│                                                                              │
│ ### 4. Proof artifacts vs. proof completion                                  │
│                                                                              │
│ `core/cell-engine/proof-artifacts/proof-4-of-7.json` is strong evidence that │
│ proof tracking exists and includes binary identity details [2][5].           │
│ But the same artifact marks scenarios 5–7 as `PENDING` [2][3][5].            │
│                                                                              │
│ Decision: **Classify cell-engine proof artifacts as                          │
│ experimental/proof-tracking, not completed proof of full runtime             │
│ capability** [3][5].                                                         │
│                                                                              │
